<h2>Getting Started with CronKit</h2>
<p>CronKit is a native batch job scheduling framework for Salesforce.  You can start with the built-in batch features, setting up scheduled jobs for the removal of out-of-date tasks and events, or you can extend CronKit and develop your own custom batch jobs using Apex.
 Sample code and configuration instructions are available at <a href="https://www.linvio.com/cronkit.php" target="_blank">www.linvio.com</a></p>

<p><strong>Ready-To-Run Batch Jobs</strong></p>
<p>CronKit come with a built-in Cleanup Script that can be configured and scheduled to run by creating a new Batch Job object. </p>
<p>1. Be sure to check the "Enable CronKit Batch Trigger" checkbox on the CronKit configuration record under the tab "CronKit" before scheduling this script.</p>
<p>2. Make sure you have created and configured active versions of the 2 sample scheduler workflow rules that came with CronKit.</p>
<p>3. Create a new batch job record and complete the scheduling and CronKit Cleanup Script fields</p>
<p>4. Click "Start Batch Run" to run the script and begin the scheduling of subsequent jobs.</p>
<p><strong>Custom Batch Jobs</strong></p>
<p>1. Install the sample batch job trigger in a developer account or your sandbox and modify it to run the Apex method(s) you have created.</p>
<p>2. Clone and configure the sample CronKit workflow rules to fire when your Batch_Run__c objects are created and updated.</p>
<p>3. Test and publish your custom batch job trigger to your production Salesforce account.
<p>4. Build and schedule batch jobs to run your Apex method(s).</p>
